lair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":55309,"username":"LPryor","name":"","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/lpryor/{size}/220287_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":32728,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"177 & 429 Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/programming-leds-candle-vs-rio-vs-ardunio/442223/7","custom_user_title":"177 & 429 Mentor","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3240478,"name":"","username":"LPryor","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/lpryor/{size}/220287_2.png","created_at":"2023-10-13T22:14:11.524Z","cooked":"<p>We’ve had the same issue for FTC and FRC. We assumed it was something pressing the button during movement. We were actually planning on using the pwm ports directly. But we also are testing the CANDL.</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":18,"updated_at":"2023-10-13T22:14:11.524Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":190,"readers_count":189,"score":48.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":442223,"topic_slug":"programming-leds-candle-vs-rio-vs-ardunio","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":32728,"username":"Molly_Connolly","name":"Molly Connolly","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7feea3/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55309,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Mentor 8280, President Motor City Alliance"},"post_url":"/t/programming-leds-candle-vs-rio-vs-ardunio/442223/8","custom_user_title":"Mentor 8280, President Motor City Alliance","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3240479,"name":"Brett B Bonner","username":"bbonner","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bbonner/{size}/155176_2.png","created_at":"2023-10-13T22:21:49.372Z","cooked":"<p>This topic comes up frequently on this forum; you will find many other posts with good information.  I summarized my thoughts on the topic quite recently in <a href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/practical-led-lighting/440408/5">this post</a>, so I won’t repeat the details here.  The TL;DR is: for my team, the Rio is the clear winner (least cost, most flexible, easy to use).</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":18,"updated_at":"2023-10-13T22:21:49.372Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":184,"readers_count":183,"score":61.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":442223,"topic_slug":"programming-leds-candle-vs-rio-vs-ardunio","display_username":"Brett B Bonner","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/practical-led-lighting/440408/5","internal":true,"reflection":false,"title":"Practical LED Lighting","clicks":37}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48574,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"6328  Mentor - Electrical/Controls"},"post_url":"/t/programming-leds-candle-vs-rio-vs-ardunio/442223/9","custom_user_title":"6328  Mentor - Electrical/Controls","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3240489,"name":"Steven Carmain","username":"Steven_Carmain","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/f07891/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-10-13T23:23:59.003Z","cooked":"<p>We have used custom circuits for a couple years (Arduinos, LightDrive), but for the offseason events this season, we switched to using the Rio directly.  It was really easy to use.</p>
<p>Advantages:</p>
<ul>
<li>The lights are programmed with the robot, so updating for strategy/indications are cake.  (otherwise, you have to send commands over SPI/I2C/Serial, and you just doubled your work)</li>
<li>Because the AddressableLED uses the ASIC to send the W2812B pulses, there is very little loop time hit.  My measurements put it at ~0.1ms loop time hit to drive 74 LEDs.</li>
<li>Edit: You can run the AddressableLED in simulation for testing purposes, which I don’t think the other solutions support.</li>
<li>CANdle uses CAN bandwidth, and we were at around 80% usage without lights, so we didn’t want to take the risk with CANdle.</li>
<li>With the Rev Blinkin, it’s control is a PWM signal.  FRC locks the PWM ports while disabled, so you can’t switch patterns while disabled. (I have never used it, but when we used the LightDrive in PWM mode, I ran into this)</li>
<li>Neat trick, when the LEDs light, you know you can connect to the robot Wifi then, as the boot time of the Rio is right around the Radio boot time (I think the Rio waits till it gets an IP before it starts your robot code).  If your pattern changes every loop, you can see when the Rio falls behind in loop time too. (as your pattern stops) <img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/images/emoji/google/wink.png?v=12" title=":wink:" class="emoji" alt=":wink:" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20"></li>
</ul>
<p>Notes:</p>
<ul>
<li>The AddressableLED class only supports 1 LED string (as of 2023, [Edit] and 2024).  Now, you can daisy chain strips together around your robot to get more lights.  Also, you can use a Y cable to address 2 strips with the same commands (we actually double Y cable our leds for 4 strips of identical commands for left/right side, and front/rear side of our arm).</li>
<li>The practical limits are ~500 LEDs to update at 50Hz (the 20ms looptime), and ~20mA per LED to drive with a max of 60mA/LED if they are white.</li>
<li>You will want to trim out the power wire from the Rio PWM cable and splice in a 12-5V converter like <a href="https://www.amazon.com/12v-5v-Converter-Regulator-Transformer/dp/B08PP6LMM1" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">this</a> to power the strip.  The Rio only has 2A of power and it’s 6V (it will work, we did testing with a 10 LED strip directly to the Rio and nothing blew up for a couple hours, just really bright).</li>
<li>We made the LEDs a subsystem so you could schedule commands to run on it.  It made it pretty easy to switch between commands, fire commands when needed, and set a default pattern during a match vs disabled.  (We actually had 2 subsystems, one for the arm length, and one for a strip in front, the arm ones were the master, and the front strip just manipulated a section of the strip, but since it was a separate subsystem, you could have 2 patterns running at the same time)</li>
<li>This year, we had 4x strips of 47 LEDs down our arms and 27 in the front for 215 total (only 74 actually addressed though).</li>
